(EXPLOSION ROARS)

42
00:04:11,479 --> 00:04:13,319
(SCREAMING)

43
00:04:26,279 --> 00:04:27,919
WOMAN OVER RADIO:
...claimed responsibility for the attack

44
00:04:28,079 --> 00:04:29,879
at the International School in Manila.

45
00:04:30,039 --> 00:04:31,519
MAN: Your father was a reader.

46
00:04:31,719 --> 00:04:35,839
Churchill, of course, but also Faulkner
and books about Tecumseh.

47
00:04:35,999 --> 00:04:39,839
He loved artists who painted people
with bodies that looked like boxes.

48
00:04:39,999 --> 00:04:41,799
I'd give him hell about that.

49
00:04:41,959 --> 00:04:43,799
He'd just say,
"You gotta look harder."

50
00:04:46,559 --> 00:04:49,719
(MAN SHOUTING ORDERS
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE)

51
00:04:52,799 --> 00:04:55,599
Ambassador Margullies had long
been a strong supporter

52
00:04:55,759 --> 00:04:58,999
ofjoint counterterrorism operations
conducted within this region.

53
00:04:59,159 --> 00:05:02,879
Not one group has yet claimed responsibility
for the attacks on the International School.

54
00:05:03,039 --> 00:05:04,799
- Here's your coffee, Rorke.
- Thank you, ma'am.

55
00:05:04,959 --> 00:05:06,879
- How's it going?
- Hey, you want the usual?

56
00:05:07,039 --> 00:05:09,319
- Sounds good, thank you.
- You're late again, Dave.

57
00:05:10,879 --> 00:05:12,519
(LAUGHS)
I didn't say anything.

58
00:05:12,719 --> 00:05:14,839
What do you got
going on over here?

59
00:05:19,279 --> 00:05:22,559
- Are you serious, man?
- We're not telling anyone yet.

60
00:05:22,719 --> 00:05:24,119
You a little nervous, though, huh?

61
00:05:24,319 --> 00:05:25,719
Last time I checked,
they don't come with directions.

62
00:05:25,879 --> 00:05:27,359
Yeah, tell me about it.

63
00:05:27,519 --> 00:05:28,439
- Hey.
- Hey.

64
00:05:28,599 --> 00:05:30,319
My man here is having a baby.

65
00:05:30,479 --> 00:05:32,719
Hey, congratulations.

66
00:05:32,879 --> 00:05:34,839
Hey, everybody,
Rorke's having a baby.

67
00:05:35,039 --> 00:05:36,599
- (CHEERING)
- WOMAN: Congratulations, Rorke!

68
00:05:36,759 --> 00:05:38,359
- Whoo!
- (APPLAUSE)

69
00:05:38,519 --> 00:05:41,279
- What did I just say?
- Ah, don't worry about it, man.

70
00:05:41,439 --> 00:05:45,359
You're gonna be awesome. I'm so excited
for you, man. You're gonna be a good dad.

71
00:05:45,519 --> 00:05:48,479
Hey, tomorrow Jackie and I
are heading down to the beach.

72
00:05:48,639 --> 00:05:51,839
Bring Sandy and the kids.
I'll bring an extra board for you.

73
00:05:51,999 --> 00:05:54,039
- You know I don't surf.
- I know you don't surf, but it'll be good

74
00:05:54,199 --> 00:05:55,479
- to get the families together.
- All right.

75
00:05:55,679 --> 00:05:59,239
But now that you've told everyone in the bar,
try and contain yourself tomorrow.

76
00:06:00,079 --> 00:06:01,319
I will try.

77
00:06:01,519 --> 00:06:04,839
(BEEPING)

78
00:06:09,719 --> 00:06:12,239
DAVE: "Look harder,"
your father would say.

79
00:06:12,399 --> 00:06:15,919
I always knew he wasn'tjust talking
about those boxy abstract paintings.

80
00:06:17,759 --> 00:06:21,759
There's threats everywhere,
and the world is draped in camouflage.

81
00:06:23,079 --> 00:06:26,279
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

82
00:06:30,479 --> 00:06:33,279
(CHILDREN LAUGHING, CHATTERING)

83
00:06:33,439 --> 00:06:35,239
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

84
00:06:35,399 --> 00:06:36,639
(CHEERING)

85
00:06:43,959 --> 00:06:46,599
CHRISTO: Huh?
(SPEAKS SPANISH)

86
00:06:56,519 --> 00:06:58,799
(CHEERING CONTINUES)

87
00:07:08,919 --> 00:07:11,559
(VEHICLE APPROACHING)

88
00:07:22,199 --> 00:07:24,639
Hey, I'll be right down, all right?

89
00:07:26,119 --> 00:07:27,439
Whatever you say, Boss.

90
00:07:27,599 --> 00:07:29,239
(DOG BARKS)

91
00:07:30,439 --> 00:07:31,519
WOMAN: How was the ride?

92
00:07:31,679 --> 00:07:33,119
MAN: I left Colombia this morning.

93
00:07:33,319 --> 00:07:37,199
- Colombia to here in one day?
- Piece of cake.

94
00:07:37,359 --> 00:07:39,399
Anyway, estimates say
that Christo is worth

95
00:07:39,559 --> 00:07:41,759
- close to a billion.
- That's with a "B"?

96
00:07:41,919 --> 00:07:44,279
Yeah, and he gives back a lot
to this community over here

97
00:07:44,439 --> 00:07:47,999
with medical clinics,
schools, political donations,

98
00:07:48,159 --> 00:07:49,519
you name it, so this is the deal:

99
00:07:49,679 --> 00:07:51,519
They are extremely
loyal to him over here.

100
00:07:51,679 --> 00:07:54,159
When did the DEA hand him over to us?

101
00:07:54,319 --> 00:07:57,919
When they intercepted a 707 of his
filled with Soviet weapons.

102
00:07:58,079 --> 00:08:00,359
Listen, Langley says that
the boys over at NSA,

103
00:08:00,559 --> 00:08:03,359
they found some interesting
intercepts connecting Christo

104
00:08:03,559 --> 00:08:05,999
to a jihadist network
out of Southeast Asia.

105
00:08:06,159 --> 00:08:09,199
Apparently, Christo and one
of the guys running the network,

106
00:08:09,399 --> 00:08:10,799
they're childhood friends.

107
00:08:12,079 --> 00:08:14,159
(CAMERA CLICKING)

108
00:08:16,039 --> 00:08:18,079
DAVE: Your father's
grandfather gave up his life

109
00:08:18,279 --> 00:08:20,799
flying a B-24 in World War II.

110
00:08:20,959 --> 00:08:24,039
He kept the Liberator aloft
just long enough for everyone to jump,

111
00:08:24,199 --> 00:08:26,399
and then he went down
with the plane.

112
00:08:26,559 --> 00:08:28,599
That's the blood
that courses in your veins.

113
00:08:29,879 --> 00:08:32,919
- Daddy, can I come with you?
- You want to come with me?

114
00:08:33,079 --> 00:08:35,839
Did you feel how cold it is out there?
I'll tell you what,

115
00:08:35,999 --> 00:08:38,599
go hang out with Mommy for a little while,
help out with the baby.

116
00:08:38,799 --> 00:08:41,679
When I come back in, if you still want
to go out, I'll take you out with me.

117
00:08:41,839 --> 00:08:44,759
- Promise?
- I promise. Hurry up, go.

118
00:08:50,559 --> 00:08:52,559
- What's going on, sir?
- What's up, brother?

119
00:08:52,719 --> 00:08:55,759
- Nothing much, man.
- Now, I know you got the New York heritage,

120
00:08:55,919 --> 00:08:58,279
but this isn't exactly like
sitting back in Staten Island.

121
00:08:58,439 --> 00:09:00,399
You got to actually work hard
to get through the surf.

122
00:09:00,559 --> 00:09:01,959
- Yeah, I know.
- Twelve-plus years on the Teams,

123
00:09:02,159 --> 00:09:03,359
and you don't know
how to do this?

124
00:09:03,519 --> 00:09:05,359
Hey, wait till you
have five kids, man.

125
00:09:05,519 --> 00:09:07,399
You'll see how much time
you got to play in the surf.

126
00:09:07,559 --> 00:09:09,159
You ready to get
in the drink or what?

127
00:09:09,319 --> 00:09:10,599
All right, man, lead the way.

128
00:09:10,759 --> 00:09:12,639
- All right, don't embarrass us.
- All right.

129
00:09:12,839 --> 00:09:16,919
DAVE: Your father was my Boss,
and I was his Chief.

130
00:09:17,079 --> 00:09:20,879
What we knew about each other
strengthened our bond as operators.

131
00:09:21,039 --> 00:09:24,159
There was a brotherhood between us,

132
00:09:24,319 --> 00:09:27,119
and we depended on each other
more than a family.

133
00:09:31,559 --> 00:09:34,759
Tecumseh said,
"Although a single twig will break,

134
00:09:34,919 --> 00:09:37,039
a bundle of twigs is strong."

135
00:09:40,759 --> 00:09:42,759
(WOMAN SPEAKING SPANISH)

136
00:09:46,519 --> 00:09:48,399
OK, OK, gracias.

137
00:09:48,559 --> 00:09:50,679
Wow, this is unbelievable.

138
00:09:50,839 --> 00:09:52,919
I still can't believe you
ordered Chinese in this place.

139
00:09:53,079 --> 00:09:55,359
It's really good.

140
00:09:55,519 --> 00:09:58,479
("TE VI" PLAYS OVER RADIO)

141
00:10:01,919 --> 00:10:03,399
(CHUCKLES)

142
00:10:03,599 --> 00:10:06,159
Double word score,
18 points.

143
00:10:08,279 --> 00:10:11,679
- "Dumb"?
- Read it and weep, sugar.

144
00:10:14,119 --> 00:10:15,719
(CHUCKLES)

145
00:10:15,879 --> 00:10:17,439
I'll try not to.

146
00:10:18,519 --> 00:10:21,679
Look at this, look at this.
Thirty-eight points for me.

147
00:10:21,839 --> 00:10:23,959
"Adumbrating,"
that's not even a word.

148
00:10:24,159 --> 00:10:26,279
OK, first of all,
it's pronounced "adumbrating,"

149
00:10:26,439 --> 00:10:29,079
and it means pretending,
foreshadowing.

150
00:10:30,479 --> 00:10:32,199
- (DOORBELL BUZZES)
- Hm...

151
00:10:32,359 --> 00:10:34,679
Guess who's buying dinner
tonight, sugar.

152
00:10:34,879 --> 00:10:37,519
("TE VI" CONTINUING OVER RADIO)

153
00:10:38,559 --> 00:10:40,679
Fine.

154
00:10:40,879 --> 00:10:44,199
In most cases,
officers get tactical partners.

155
00:10:44,359 --> 00:10:47,999
Langley sets me up
with some sort of SCRABBLE hustler.

156
00:10:48,159 --> 00:10:51,039
WOMAN: SCRABBLE Yoda, OK?
Get it right.

157
00:10:51,199 --> 00:10:52,559
(SIGHS)

158
00:10:53,759 --> 00:10:55,239
- How much do I owe you?
- Nada.

159
00:10:55,439 --> 00:10:57,199
- (GUNSHOT)
- (MAN YELLS IN SPANISH)

160
00:10:57,399 --> 00:10:59,759
- Shit.
- ("TE VI" CONTINUING)

161
00:11:00,879 --> 00:11:03,199
- (GRUNTS)
- (MAN YELLING)

162
00:11:04,519 --> 00:11:06,959
- (SHOUTING IN SPANISH)
- (WOMAN GRUNTS)

163
00:11:08,479 --> 00:11:10,959
(MEN SPEAKING SPANISH)

164
00:11:18,159 --> 00:11:20,279
("TE VI" FADING)

165
00:11:21,239 --> 00:11:23,119
(TIRES SCREECH)

166
00:11:23,279 --> 00:11:25,959
(CHURCH BELL TOLLING IN DISTANCE)

167
00:11:28,999 --> 00:11:31,679
("TE VI" PLAYING ON CAR STEREO)

168
00:11:41,719 --> 00:11:43,639
(CHILDREN LAUGHING)

169
00:11:43,799 --> 00:11:46,559
DAVE: Our platoon
was headed downrange.

170
00:11:47,879 --> 00:11:49,519
We had Weimy, our sniper.

171
00:11:49,679 --> 00:11:52,639
He grew up in the middle
of the Mojave Desert.

172
00:11:52,799 --> 00:11:55,479
Most excitement he found
as a kid was bowling frozen turkeys

173
00:11:55,639 --> 00:11:57,959
down the aisle at the grocery store.

174
00:11:59,479 --> 00:12:02,479
Ray, our comms guy, our radioman,

175
00:12:02,639 --> 00:12:05,239
he grew up in East LA gangland.

176
00:12:05,399 --> 00:12:09,719
He had a Silver Star for pulling
a wounded teammate out of the fray.

177
00:12:09,879 --> 00:12:12,639
Sonny, he was made of granite.

178
00:12:12,799 --> 00:12:14,639
This guy didn't even do push-ups

179
00:12:14,799 --> 00:12:17,919
'cause he was afraid his chest
was gonna get too big.

180
00:12:18,079 --> 00:12:21,279
Ajayjoined the Teams
late in his 30s.

181
00:12:21,479 --> 00:12:23,679
He'd been a Muay Thai fighter
early in life.

182
00:12:23,839 --> 00:12:26,959
Before that, he grew up
dirt-poor in Trinidad.

183
00:12:28,959 --> 00:12:31,239
Mikey had 20 years in the Teams.

184
00:12:31,399 --> 00:12:33,959
But as humble as he was,
you'd never even know it.

185
00:12:34,159 --> 00:12:38,359
He kept a picture of his wife in his helmet
and a lock of her hair in his pocket.

186
00:12:38,519 --> 00:12:40,399
Quiet as the breeze.

187
00:12:41,439 --> 00:12:43,079
And finally, Senior Chief.

188
00:12:43,239 --> 00:12:45,639
I couldn't really
tell you much about him...

189
00:12:45,839 --> 00:12:48,159
...other than I'd rather
take a knife into a gunfight

190
00:12:48,319 --> 00:12:49,999
than have to be interrogated by him.

191
00:12:51,039 --> 00:12:52,439
(INAUDIBLE CHATTER)

192
00:12:53,799 --> 00:12:55,599
That last night at home,

193
00:12:55,759 --> 00:12:57,999
you think about how you could
have been a better dad,

194
00:12:58,159 --> 00:12:59,999
a better husband.

195
00:13:00,159 --> 00:13:03,999
That bedtime story you should have read
or that anniversary you forgot.

196
00:13:04,159 --> 00:13:06,919
You don't expect your family
to understand what you're doing,

197
00:13:07,079 --> 00:13:08,839
you just hope they'll accept it.

198
00:13:08,999 --> 00:13:12,919
When you get home, you hope you
can pick up right where you left off.

199
00:13:13,119 --> 00:13:15,559
- What up?
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)

200
00:13:15,719 --> 00:13:18,839
- You putting the wild bunch down?
- Yeah, yeah.

201
00:13:19,039 --> 00:13:22,599
Hey, Senior, you mind giving
us a couple minutes, man?

202
00:13:22,759 --> 00:13:25,039
- Nah, you got 'em, Jefe.
- Thanks.

203
00:13:26,959 --> 00:13:28,559
Hey, fellas, you know
I only got so many speeches

204
00:13:28,759 --> 00:13:31,879
in a given work-up or deployment, but, uh...

205
00:13:32,039 --> 00:13:35,759
...it's like Chief and I said right
at the beginning of this platoon:

206
00:13:35,919 --> 00:13:39,519
Once we step off on campaign, once this
bird's ready and we're downrange,

207
00:13:39,679 --> 00:13:41,959
everything back home
needs to be in balance.

208
00:13:42,119 --> 00:13:43,839
We're not gonna be worth a damn
to each other or ourselves

209
00:13:43,999 --> 00:13:45,679
if we get over there
and something's out of whack.

210
00:13:45,839 --> 00:13:47,679
I mean, if things
aren't right with the family,

211
00:13:47,839 --> 00:13:50,639
things aren't right with the finances
or something's off,

212
00:13:50,799 --> 00:13:54,039
it's gonna put us all out of balance, so we
need to have that tight before we launch.

213
00:13:54,239 --> 00:13:56,079
If somebody's got an issue,
bring it up.

214
00:13:56,239 --> 00:13:59,279
Chief can take care of it, I can take care
of it. Everybody's got each other's back.

215
00:13:59,439 --> 00:14:02,079
Let's make sure we lock that down
so when we're ready to roll,

216
00:14:02,239 --> 00:14:04,239
all our focus is on the mission.

217
00:14:06,319 --> 00:14:08,599
DAVE: For all those
who have been downrange,

218
00:14:08,799 --> 00:14:12,199
to us and those like us,
damn few.

219
00:14:12,359 --> 00:14:14,239
- Cheers.
- Hear, hear.

220
00:14:24,759 --> 00:14:26,119
I still like the name James.

221
00:14:26,319 --> 00:14:28,959
I'll think about it,
if it's a boy.

222
00:14:30,359 --> 00:14:31,359
Come here.

223
00:14:39,799 --> 00:14:42,679
- I'm proud of you.
- Thanks, baby.

224
00:14:45,279 --> 00:14:48,999
Hey, little one, you make sure
you keep Mama away from Aunt Carol.

225
00:14:49,159 --> 00:14:51,159
I don't like that
chain-smoking at all.

226
00:14:51,319 --> 00:14:52,759
I got it, Lieutenant.

227
00:14:52,919 --> 00:14:54,279
- OK.
- It's gonna be OK.

228
00:14:54,439 --> 00:14:57,479
- All right.
- It's gonna be fine.

229
00:15:03,039 --> 00:15:05,479
Try to keep this as long
as you can for a while, yeah?

230
00:15:05,639 --> 00:15:06,959
Anything else, Commander?

231
00:15:07,119 --> 00:15:12,079
Yeah. I'd like to be able to look into
your eyes when our first child is born.

232
00:15:12,279 --> 00:15:14,319
You know I'll do my best.

